Fig. 12 show the comparison of the SoH estimation performance of three testing protocols such as DST, HPPC, BBDST under varying temperature conditions (
5 ° C − 35 ° C
), temperature impacts the accuracy of SoH predictions for lithium-ion batteries. At low temperature (5 °C), HPPC yields the lowest MAE of 0.04, compared to 0.05 for DST and 0.06 for BBDST. However, as temperature rises to 35 °C, errors increase consistently, reaching 0.11 (HPPC), 0.12 (DST), and 0.13 (BBDST). The consistently higher MAE of BBDST reflects the difficulty of modeling SoH under highly dynamic, stressful cycling conditions, while the relatively lower errors of HPPC confirm its suitability as a benchmark protocol for extracting resistance-related features. These observations reinforce earlier findings that temperature significantly amplifies prediction uncertainty and that protocol choice strongly influences model reliability [15,16]. Moreover, the superior stability of HPPC aligns with prior work highlighting the importance of structured transient profiles for accurate and fast SoH prediction [20]. Thus, the results in Fig. 12 emphasize that accurate, temperature-aware SoH estimation requires careful protocol selection, especially for real-world applications where batteries are exposed to dynamic and thermally varying environments.

Table 9 presents the comparative results of MAE and RMSE across different models, along with bootstrap-based significance testing against the proposed LSTM–XGBoost model. The LSTM–XGBoost consistently achieves the lowest error values (MAE = 2.94, RMSE = 3.64). Bootstrap resampling confirmed that the improvements were statistically significant compared to SVM (
p =
0.009
) and RF (
p =
0.021
). The difference with ECM was borderline significant (
p =
0.056
), likely due to the limited number of test conditions. These results demonstrate that the predictive advantage of the hybrid LSTM–XGBoost framework is not only numerically superior but also statistically validated.
